esearch, Afro-Creole draws on historical, anthropological, sociological, and literary sources. Burton characterizes the emergence of Caribbean identity with three different national flavors and demonstrates how culture both reflects and impacts people's changing sense of their own political power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCreoleszHaitixReligion. 0aCreoleszJamaicaxReligion. 0aCreoleszTrinidad and TobagoxSocial life and customs. 0aGovernment, Resistance tozWest IndiesxHistory. 0aSlaveryzWest IndiesxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172243140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722431/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles